Yes — I would update it, but it is not strictly required if you already keep the code-based bypass in isFrameworkOrStaticResourceRequest(...).

Best practice is:
	•	Code-level exclusion = real protection/fix
	•	web.xml exclusion = configuration clarity + backup

So the answer is:

What is required?

Required: the Java code fix
Recommended: update web.xml too

Your current web.xml already has a lot of the right exclusions:
	•	/javax.faces.resource
	•	/css
	•	/images
	•	/js
	•	/rfRes
	•	/systemError.xhtml

That is good.

What I would add

From our discussion, add these if they are used in your app:

/a4j,
/cfRes

So your param-value can become:

/resources/rss,/resources/rest,/resources/remote,/resources/batch,/css,/images,/js,/rfRes,
/javax.faces.resource,/cfRes,/a4j,/c.xhtml,/c.faces,/verification_smfa_success.xhtml,
/verification_smfa_success.faces,/systemError.xhtml,/systemError.faces

Why update it if code already handles it?

Because:
	•	it documents the exclusion behavior clearly for the team
	•	it helps future maintainers
	•	if someone changes the helper method later, config still gives a second layer of safety

Important clarification

web.xml alone is not enough to solve your issue if the main problem was this:

nv.setBooleanValue(true);

for every valid query string.

That redirect/query-string-loss issue had to be fixed in code.
So:
	•	Do not rely only on web.xml
	•	Keep the Java fix
	•	Optionally update web.xml for completeness

My recommendation

Do both:
	1.	Keep the updated Java logic
	2.	Add /a4j and /cfRes to web.xml

That is the cleanest approach.

